title: Manly's Westpac-leased property on The Corso sells for $20m
text:
The Peterson family - of Manly pub fame - has sold its Westpac-leased commercial property on The Corso, the northern beaches suburb's famous thoroughfare, for $20.2 million.

A local doctor acquired the family's two-storey Westpac bank branch property at 32 The Corso, closing the deal reached through an expressions of interest campaign at a yield of 4.92 per cent.

32 The Corso, Manly sells for $20.2 million at a yield of 4.92 per cent. Supplied

The 815sq m property is leased to Westpac until 2024 with a 20-year option.

Cushman & Wakefield’s Ryan Cross and Aaron McLean and Patrick Kelleher from Pine Property who brokered the sale said they fielded 300 enquiries and 13 offers.

"Achieving net yields of sub 5 per cent in the current market, even for asset sales up to $20 million, demonstrates that the strength of confidence in Sydney’s commercial property market is very healthy,” Mr Mclean said.

Earlier this year, another high-profile Manly property sold for a big sum. Sydney property tycoon Sam Arnaout's Iris Capital bought Manly's Hotel Steyne for about $65 million.

The Peterson family is known for owning The Corso's main pub, the newly refurbished Ivanhoe Hotel.
description: Manly pub-owning Peterson family has sold a commercial holding to a local doctor.
